metadata.description:
構造の息吹 | BREATH OF SCULPTURES

The digital realm knows no end, offering us an infinite canvas to explore, create, and connect.

metadata.name: LAISSEZ FAIRE #34
metadata.description:
In creating this piece, I found myself drawn to the intersection where technology meets literature, a space where code and creativity become inseparable. It's a unique blend of Aldous Huxley's "Brave New World" and the unpredictable nature of AI-generated visuals.

Huxley's dystopian vision always struck a chord with me, especially in today's rapidly advancing technological landscape. I saw parallels between his world and the way generative art evolves - both shaped by their environments, reflecting fears, hopes, and the inherent chaos of their times.

But what really fascinated me was how human touch still played a role. Much like the characters in "Brave New World" wrestling with destiny, the AI visuals in my work, though algorithmically birthed, were guided by my hand. They're not just a reflection of the text but a response to it, engaging in a dialogue that goes beyond mere replication.

This isn't just a generative token; it's a question, a conversation. It's my way of exploring where we stand at this crossroads of art, literature, and technology. In crafting this piece, I found myself wondering, what does our Brave New World look like? How do we balance the precision of code with the fluidity of human emotion? And in a world increasingly dictated by algorithms, where do we fit in?

I invite you to join me in this exploration. Let's unravel the tapestry, decode the symbols, and discover what it means to be human in a world where art and AI coalesce.

- Press "T" to save the text contained within the composition, derived from it´s specific chapter 
- Press "S" to save a .png of the composition

metadata.name: The Pure Zone #42
metadata.description:
"The Pure Zone" is a captivating and visually stunning form of artistic expression. 
It is characterized by its use of clean lines, minimalistic designs, and a focus on creating a sense of purity and tranquility.
I employed a limited color palette, consisting mainly of neutral tones such as whites, grays, and pastels. This deliberate choice enhances the overall sense of calm and simplicity in the artwork.
The subject in "The Pure Zone" is abstract representations of emotions or concepts. The aim is to evoke a feeling of serenity and inner peace through this artwork.
One notable feature of "The Pure Zone" is its meticulous attention to detail. Each line and stroke is purposefully placed to create a harmonious composition that draws the viewer's eye into the artwork. This attention to detail adds depth and dimension to the piece while maintaining its overall minimalist aesthetic.

"The Pure Zone" serves as a visual reminder to find beauty in simplicity and embrace moments of stillness in our busy lives.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #181
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: Gravity #4
metadata.description:
Gravity is when you can't set/keep your own course and, eventually, crush and break in pieces.

This is an animated piece and it's performance will depend on the power of the machine it is run.
The same configuration is rendered on different color palettes and it's looping endlessly.

The work is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Initial resolution is the screen resolution. Although the piece is supposed to look more or less the same no matter the resolution.

The royalties goes to me (40%), @toxi(30%) and the minter(30%).


Keyboard shortcuts

- space bar : pause/resume animation 
- 2 : download png @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : download png @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: Fantasmagoria #95
metadata.description:
ℹ see Phantasmagoria - noun - A dreamlike state where real and imagined elements are blurred together.

💡The work on this series started with an exploration on perceived shapes in a complex generator using noise and randomisation.

👻The deeper I was going into my exploration, the more I encountered scary or spooky iterations.

🧙‍♂️Inspired by the art initiated by Paul Philidor or Étienne-Gaspard Robertson, I decided to explore the creation of alternate, disturbing, undefined forms in the dark.

👋🏻 Personally, Fantasmagoria is a catharcis, and might be the last piece of my "dark" phase. Releasing this project means a lot, not only from the work I've put in it, but from the chapter of my life it closes.

metadata.name: Kunza #107
metadata.description:
In 1949, the last known native speaker of Kunza died in the Atacama desert of Chile, leaving behind only fragments of a language that stretched back to when the Incans ruled the region. The textures, patterns, and colors in this project are not intended to be historically accurate: they tell a story. They are my attempt to reach into the past and imagine a vibrant history that is increasingly inaccessible.

Features include weave design, symbol layout, symbol style, and color palette.

After the image has fully rendered, pressing ‘w’, ‘r’, or ‘c’ will toggle different elements of the image, and pressing ‘s’ will download a PNG file.

p5.js

metadata.name: The Incredible Contraption #3
metadata.description:
The Incredible contraption is part of the fxhackathon 2023: co-creation interfaces.

Build, Iterate, Create

An attempt to give any collector a fun and powerful tool to create generative art and a new kind of minting experience.

Controls :
- Pan with left mouse button
- Zoom with mouse wheel or middle mouse button.
- Click the camera icon to access the export menu, where you can generate high resolution PNG files of the artwork, but also of the plans for the contraptions that created it.
- You can adjust the anti-aliasing by clicking the icon with small dots. This can drastically impact performances.
- You can pause / restart the simulation by using the controls at the bottom of the window.

The generated artwork use WebGL features, and so a dedicated graphics card is recommended.
Google Chrome recommended

For more information on the project, consult the fx(text) linked below.
The source code for the project can be found at this adress : https://github.com/ULuIQ12/fxhashhackathon-2023

metadata.name: Automatic #335
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.

metadata.name: SCHNEEWALD #89
metadata.description:
SCHNEEWALD is the second release in a row of about 12 tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years.

This project explores an approach to trees with snow using a recursive algorithm and includes Three traits: a density layer for the amount of trees and another layer for the amount snow and a third for how strong the branches bend.

Rendering progress indicated on the top left border
Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png

Artist notes:
Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

I experienced it in all sorts of seasonal change, packed with snow is definitely among the most amazing! 

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: https://e-art.co/project/schneewald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.

metadata.name: Schwere See #158
metadata.description:
Schwere See (...which is german for "Heavy Seas") this work creates completely generative ocean worlds between the real and the surreal. what is real? when do we feel reality? i guess as with many other things, we feel reality best when we're deprived of it. That might be the reason why it never ceases to fascinate us to both exaggerate and abstract nature and reality - maybe even at the same time. that's where this work tries to go... giving my best to create realistic looking waves out of hmm... thin electron-gas..., and then disrupt those from realism by unnaturally exaggerating waveforms and abstracting the display to a few colors and lines - ...well, not so few of the latter, actually ;-) beware: this needs a good GPU (at least here in 2023) to properly run in realtime. stills can still be rendered on a low end machine with on-board graphics, but for realtime playing you'd need some proper dedicated graphics card. and of course it wont run fast (or maybe not all) on your mobile phone (except maybe on a very high end device). the different mints vary in wave shape, color, camera view, animation speed, aspect ratio, frame style, hatching density, field of view, and more. some color schemes are based on pre-chosen palettes (slightly varied though), but others are wildly random-generated. there's always some risk in randomness, but lets give the error some chance to surprise us - this is one of the many benefits of generative art. as generative art can do so much more than just generate/show an image i feel almost obliged to add the possibility to animate/inteact. however, this extra control shall not be chosen without some considerations. you don't want a strobingly wild animation above your fireplace or in a doctors waiting room. nor is it motion-wise very inspiring to have subtle image stills hanging in a dancefloor. so, by default when in animation mode (-key) the scene is very slowly and steadily changing - some pieces faster, some slower. however, by pressing you can toggle to a sped up animation of waves, clouds, and scene rotation. btw, going faster in nav-mode also speeds up the wave animation. (...so be careful when you accelerate! the ocean is not a ponyfarm.) mouse/keyboard functions: ..........rotate view .........zoom in/out ...............start animation (or append '&AnimEnable=1' to the url) +<1><2><3><4>...make png screenshot in 1/2/3/4-fold resolution

...................same as +<3> ...................toggle nav-mode - navigate/fly through scene /.........accelerate in nav-mode /.......decelerate in nav-mode /.......rotate left in nav-mode /......rotate right in nav-mode ...................fast animation mode (speeds up animation) some technical info: technically this is a raymarched scene. the distance field of the waves is constructed my many localized rotations on many different scales. for the hatching no actual lines are being drawn. it is archieved by applying periodic functions in world-position-space as halftone patterns to the actual image color. the frequency of these halftone-functions thereby depending on screen-position-derivatives.
